    <question>
        <prompt>What impact did the Underwood-Simmons Tariff have on the American economy?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It raised tariff rates to record highs</option>
            <option letter="b">It significantly reduced tariff rates</option>
            <option letter="c">It eliminated all tariffs</option>
            <option letter="d">It only affected luxury goods</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The Underwood-Simmons Tariff of 1913 significantly reduced tariff rates for the first time since the Civil War, marking a major shift in U.S. economic policy under Wilson's administration.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What was the significance of the 16th Amendment?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It banned alcohol</option>
            <option letter="b">It established federal income tax</option>
            <option letter="c">It gave women voting rights</option>
            <option letter="d">It abolished slavery</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The 16th Amendment, ratified in 1913, established the federal government's right to collect income tax directly from citizens, dramatically changing federal revenue collection.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How did the creation of the Federal Trade Commission affect business?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It eliminated all regulations</option>
            <option letter="b">It investigated unfair business practices</option>
            <option letter="c">It set all prices</option>
            <option letter="d">It managed international trade only</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The Federal Trade Commission, established in 1914, was empowered to investigate and prevent unfair business practices, adding another layer of federal oversight to business activities.</explanation>
